rt surgery or a broken leg, there is no relaxing convalescence and nothing to be learned (except, perhaps, who your friends are). It leaves you weakened and bewildered, unsure why you got sick or how you got well, praying that it never happens again but certain that it will. Scialabba documents his own struggles and draws from them insights that may prove useful to fellow-sufferers and general readers alike. In the place of dispensable banalities—"Hold on," "You will feel better," and so on—he offers an account of how it's been for him, in the hope that doing so might prove helpful to others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDepressed personsvBiographyzUnited States. 0aDepressed personszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aDepressed persons-United States-Biography. 0aDepression, MentalvCase studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh  acauses of depression.  achronic depression.  acrisis of faith.  adepression survivor.  apersonal story of depression.  apsychiatric drugs.  apsychiatric profession.  atherapy.  atreatment of depression.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069044640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9780812296877?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812296877423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812296877/original  a978-3-11-069044-6  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles